1 (4) (a) Meetings of the commission shall be conducted according to KRS 61.805 to
2 61.850.
3 (b) The commission shall meet at least twice within each calendar year.
4 (c) Eight (8) voting members of the commission shall constitute a quorum for
5 the transaction of business.
6 (d) Each voting member of the commission shall have one (1) vote, with all
7 actions being taken by an affirmative vote of the majority of members
8 present.
9 (5) The commission may contract with any public or private agency or any individual
10 for research, the gathering of information, the printing and publication of
11 reports, consulting, or for any other purposes necessary to discharge the duties of
12 the commission.
13 (6) The department shall promulgate administrative regulations in accordance with
14 KRS Chapter 13A to:
15 (a) Establish a grant application process for eligible organizations;
16 (b) Award moneys from the positive youth development fund established in
17 Section 3 of this Act to eligible organizations to fund positive youth
18 development programming impacting children and youth in Kentucky; and
19 (c) Identify and coordinate with a grantmaking entity to develop applications
20 and reporting requirements, monitor utilization of granted funds,
21 administer quality control, and evaluate services or grant funds to fulfill
22 these duties.
23 SECTION 3. A NEW SECTION OF KRS CHAPTER 210 IS CREATED TO
24 READ AS FOLLOWS:
25 (1) There is hereby established in the State Treasury a trust and agency account to be
26 known as the positive youth development fund. The fund shall consist of:
27 (a) Moneys received by the Commonwealth, counties, consolidated local
Page 5 of 16
HB068610.100 - 1116 - XXXX 3/27/2026 10:29 AM GA

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS HB 686/GA
1 governments, urban-county governments, and cities of the Commonwealth
2 in any settlement, judgement, or bankruptcy proceeding against any social
3 media company or person related to harms against children and youth to
4 the extent that it is not inconsistent with an order of a court of competent
5 jurisdiction; and
6 (b) Any other moneys received from state appropriations, gifts, grants, federal
7 funds, and any other source not prohibited by law.
8 (2) The fund shall be administered by the cabinet.
9 (3) Amounts deposited in the fund shall be used for the purposes described in
10 Sections 1 to 3 of this Act and for no other purpose.
11 (4) Notwithstanding KRS 45.229, fund amounts not expended at the close of a fiscal
12 year shall not lapse but shall be carried forward into the next fiscal year.
13 (5) The commission shall reserve ten percent (10%) of the funds to administer the
14 grant program and provide technical assistance to organizations applying for and
15 administering grants under Sections 1 to 3 of this Act.
16 (6) Moneys in the funds shall be distributed no less than annually.
17 (7) (a) The Office of the Attorney General may recover its reasonable costs of
18 litigation in accordance with KRS 48.005 from moneys received from a
19 legal settlement, judgement, or bankruptcy proceedings related to litigation
20 against social media companies.
21 (b) The Office of the Attorney General may recover any direct costs, including
22 employee time, used to perform or administer the duties required by
23 Sections 1 to 3 of this Act. The Office of the Attorney General shall report
24 all such recovered costs to the commission no less than annually.
25 Section 4. KRS 200.503 is amended to read as follows:
26 As used in KRS 200.501 to 200.509, unless the context otherwise requires:
27 (1) "Child with a behavioral health need" means a child or transition-age youth with, or
Page 6 of 16
HB068610.100 - 1116 - XXXX 3/27/2026 10:29 AM GA

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS HB 686/GA
1 at risk of developing, an emotional disability, substance use disorder, or mental,
2 emotional, or behavioral needs;
3 (2) "Child with an emotional disability" means a child or transition-age youth with a
4 clinically significant disorder of thought, mood, perception, orientation, memory, or
5 behavior that is listed in the current edition of the American Psychiatric
6 Association's Diagnostic and Statistical Manual of Mental Disorders and seriously
7 limits a child's capacity to function in the home, school, or community;
8 (3) "Child with a serious emotional disability" means a child or transition-age youth
9 with a clinically significant disorder of thought, mood, perception, orientation,
10 memory, or behavior that is listed in the current edition of the American Psychiatric
11 Association's Diagnostic and Statistical Manual of Mental Disorders and that:
12 (a) Presents substantial limitations that have persisted for at least one (1) year or
13 are judged by a mental health professional to be at high risk of continuing for
14 one (1) year without professional intervention in at least two (2) of the
15 following five (5) areas: "Self-care," defined as the ability to provide, sustain,
16 and protect his or herself at a level appropriate to his or her age;
17 "Interpersonal relationships," defined as the ability to build and maintain
18 satisfactory relationships with peers and adults; "Family life," defined as the
19 capacity to live in a family or family type environment; "Self-direction,"
20 defined as the child's ability to control his or her behavior and to make
21 decisions in a manner appropriate to his or her age; and "Education," defined
22 as the ability to learn social and intellectual skills from teachers in available
23 educational settings;
24 (b) Is a Kentucky resident and is receiving residential treatment for emotional
25 disability through the interstate compact;
26 (c) The Department for Community Based Services has removed the child from
27 the child's home and has been unable to maintain the child in a stable setting
Page 7 of 16
HB068610.100 - 1116 - XXXX 3/27/2026 10:29 AM GA

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS HB 686/GA
1 due to behavioral health needs; or
2 (d) Is a person under twenty-one (21) years of age meeting the criteria of
3 paragraph (a) of this subsection and who was receiving services prior to age
4 eighteen (18) that must be continued for therapeutic benefit;
5 (4) "Least restrictive alternative mode of treatment" means treatment given in the least
6 confining setting which will provide a child or transition-age youth with an
7 emotional disability or serious emotional disability appropriate treatment or care
8 consistent with accepted professional practice. For purposes of this section, least
9 restrictive alternative mode of treatment may include an institutional placement;
10 (5) "Positive youth development programming" has the same meaning as in Section
11 1 of this Act;
12 (6) "System of care" means a spectrum of effective, community-based services and
13 supports for children and transition-age youth with or at risk of developing
14 behavioral health needs and their families, that is organized into a coordinated
15 network, builds meaningful partnerships with families and youth, and addresses
16 their cultural and linguistic needs, in order to help them to function better at home,
17 in school, in the community, and throughout life; and
18 (7)[(6)] "Transition-age youth" means individuals between the ages of sixteen (16)
19 and twenty-five (25).
